<DOCNO> AP900420-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
its carpenter bill beatons job to make sure 
that when the speaker of the house of representatives flies off the 
handle the handle wont fly off his gavel 
beaton and his threeman crew in the us capitol carpentry shop 
produce about 50 handtooled gavels every year for the speakers 
use in admonishing the often rambunctious house to shut up and 
proceed with business 
it takes a sturdy gavel to silence a chamber full of legislators 
whose backslapping gossip and guffaws are stealing an orators 
thunder but beaton says his 14inch gavels of american sugar maple 
are equal to the task 
they can last for years if you dont abuse them beaton 
says one handle cracked when the gavel was hit real hard years 
ago im told but i guarantee you the head will never come off the 
handle 
the gavels are banged on a sounding board thats even tougher 
beaton fashions them from an expensive imported wood called lignum 
vitae or ironwood once used to make selflubricating bearings for 
old ships its so hard and dense that it sinks in water 
its practically bulletproof and it makes just the right 
sound beaton says other woods are too soft and wont echo 
but when the speaker hits his gavel on this ironwood board you can 
hear it all over the chamber 
even using a new electrically powered lathe that shapes gavels 
from a pattern somewhat like the machines that make duplicate car 
keys the 45yearold shop foreman spends up to two hours making a 
single gavel 
starting with a block of raw wood beaton makes grooves bevels 
and flutes with an assortment of hand chisels and woodburning 
devices and applies several finishing coats of clear acrylic 
lacquer 
beaton follows a fixed design that he says has been traditional 
for a century or more though nobody knows for sure 
when i came here nearly seven years ago i was told this is 
the way weve always made them and i should make them just like 
this he says ive never done it any other way 
the shiny blondhued gavels which beaton estimates are worth 
75 apiece are kept in a drawer at the speakers marbletopped 
rostrum for the exclusive use of the speaker or the legislator he 
appoints to preside over the house during floor action on 
legislation 
although a washington newspaper article published in 1923 
claimed that some years ago it was not unusual for 100 gavels or 
more to be smashed in one congress broken gavels are a rarity 
today 
their replacement is necessary instead because the speakers 
like to autograph their gavels and present them as gifts to 
constituents friends or to fellow legislators who have steered 
major bills to final passage 
veteran house parliamentarians recall that some house speakers 
