farmers trying to reduce use of chemicals 
would get millions of dollars in help from the federal government 
under legislation approved by the senate agriculture committee 
the research section of the panels 1990 farm bill approved 
thursday includes 40 million annually during the fiveyear life 
of the measure for a new lowinput sustainable agriculture program 
sometimes called organic farming the method employs natural 
methods for controlling pests and promotes crop rotation to sustain 
the soil 
traditionally the government has promoted farming methods that 
encourage use of chemicals this year for example it is spending 
only 45 million on sustainable agriculture 
farmers across the nation want to reduce chemical use and they 
want help from washington to do it said sen patrick leahy 
dvt chairman of the agriculture committee its time we 
offered some real help not just idle words 
the bill would also authorize 10 million each year for training 
the nations 5500 extension agents in nonchemical farming methods 
other provisions of the bill include 
establishment of a groundwater office in the agriculture 
department to determine the extent of damage done by agricultural 
chemicals to drinking water supplies and what to do about it 
a usda study of the effects of climate change on food crops and 
forests 
400 million over five years for research grants to companies 
