<TEXT>
two of every three aids patients suffer a 
mental decline that may be caused by an aids virus protein that 
forces brain cells to absorb a lethal dose of calcium harvard 
university researchers said in a study published today 
the study suggests that a calciumblocking drug already in wide 
use may be able to protect the brain cells and prevent patients 
from developing what is known as the aids dementia complex 
dr stuart a lipton a researcher at harvard and the childrens 
hospital in boston said more studies must be conducted however 
before the calciumblocking drug could be safely used for aids 
patients 
in the study appearing today in the journal science lipton and 
three coauthors said a laboratory experiment proved that minute 
amounts of an aids virus protein gp120 can cause nerve cells to 
die by forcing the cells to absorb up to 33 times their normal 
amount of calcium 
an additional experiment lipton said thursday showed that the 
calcium blocking drug nimodipine could protect nerve cells from the 
effects of gp120 
nimodipine not only blocks the rise of calcium but also 
prevents cell death lipton said in a telephone interview 
the experiment was performed in laboratory dishes using rodent 
nerve cells experiments using human nerve cells are planned he 
said 
lipton cautioned that although nimodipine worked to protect the 
nerve cells in the laboratory there is no proof that it would work 
on human cells or in human patients 
nimodipine would not treat the underlying infection but there 
is hope and its just hope that it might prevent the neurological 
manifestations he said its not a sure bet to work in these 
patients 
lipton said before nimodipine is used by aids patients 
researchers need to make sure it would not affect the action of 
antiviral drugs used to fight the aids infection 
many studies have shown that aids dementia complex develops as 
the immune deficiency disease progresses the dementia effect can 
cause patients to lose the ability to walk reason or function 
normally 
the cause of the brain problem has remained a mystery because 
researchers have not been able to isolate the human 
immunodeficiency virus which causes aids from the brain tissue of 
affected patients 
the harvard study suggests that the dementia is caused by a 
reaction to the gp120 protein and not by a direct viral infection 
of brain cells 
douglas brenneman a researcher at the governments national 
institute of child health and human development said his lab 
conducted experiments similar to the harvard studies and also found 
that gp120 could kill some types of brain cells 
im very pleased to see it the harvard study because it 
confirms our finding he said a vanishingly small amount of 
gp120 is lethal to the nerve cells 
brenneman said the harvard use of nimodipine to protect the 
cells is intriguing but that more study would be needed before 
the drug could be used on aids patients 
lipton said his group used two types of gp120 a highly purified 
form and a specimen removed from the blood of aids patients the 
harvard experiment showed that both types of gp120 would kill the 
nerve cells 
the protein gp120 coats the surface of the hiv virus that causes 
aids lipton said the virus can shed this protein like you would 
take off a coat and the protein has been found in brain tissue 
from aids patients 
both lipton and brenneman said they dont understand precisely 
how gp120 forces nerve cells to absorb lethal levels of calcium 
liptons coauthors in the study were evan b dreyer peter k 
kaiser and jeffrey t offermann all with harvard medical school 
and related institutions 
science is the journal of the american association for the 
advancement of science 
</TEXT>
