<TEXT>
a sharp drop in government payments in recent 
years continues to bear heavily on farm income prospects 
for example according to agriculture department economists in 
1986 the net cash income of farmers rose 11 percent to a record 
then of 518 billion from 467 billion in 1985 the first time 
over the 50 billion mark 
meanwhile direct federal payments to farmers soared 53 percent 
to 118 percent in 1986 from 77 billion the year before 
net cash income focuses on the value of commodities sold in a 
calendar year plus government payments less all costs the 
departments economic research service said in the april issue of 
agricultural outlook magazine 
in 1987 net cash income continued its recordsetting pace 
rising to 545 billion a 5 percent increase direct payments rose 
42 percent to a record 167 billion 
but drought ravaged crops in 1988 and forced market prices to 
shoot up although disaster payments soared the overall effect was 
to cool off total federal payments to farmers 
as market prices rose that lessened the need for paying out so 
much as deficiency payments to help bridge the gap between 
market levels and target prices used to compute the subsidies 
nationally according to usda figures net cash income in 1988 
climbed to a record of 572 billion while direct government 
payments edged down to 145 billion 
one characteristic of the bulge in 1988 net cash income was that 
many farmers even some who lost crops to drought were able to 
sell commodities stored from previous harvests at the higher market 
prices that counted as cash income in the calendar year 
in 1989 with most commodity market prices still much higher 
than they had been before the drought and the consequent 
tightening of us inventories farmers put more land back into 
crops thereby incurring larger expenses 
the upshot was a dip in net cash income in 1989 to around 53 
billion according to current usda estimates it was still much 
higher than at any time prior to 1986 federal payments dropped to 
less than 11 billion in 1989 down 25 percent from 1988 and 33 
percent below the 1987 peak 
payments are projected to drop another 15 percent this year 
the report said most of the decrease reflects less disaster 
assistance 
the disaster aid last year totaled nearly 3 billion but may be 
less than 500 million in 1990 barring widespread drought 
according to a new outlook report for may 1990 net cash income 
is expected to be in the range of 54 billion to 58 billion 
unchanged from the april forecast federal payments could drop to 
between 9 billion and 10 billion 
</TEXT>
