<TEXT>
some london subway riders are sniffing the 
fragrance of apple blossoms and hyacinths instead of what one 
transport official calls the armpit atmosphere usually wafting 
through the citys dank tunnels 
a pilot project that began thursday will scent subway cars on 
the busy east london line which carries 6 million people each year 
between whitechapel and new cross gate under the thames river and 
through 61 miles of tunnels nearly 150 years old 
passengers generally approved of the new sweet smells but not 
without reservation 
its better than the usual smell of wet dog said john 
oconnor on his way to work at a london hospital i just hope 
they dont put on too much 
ian derbyshire general manager of the east london line who is 
overseeing the project said we conducted a survey last year and 
people did not appreciate the armpit atmosphere 
there was a certain lavatorial smell which is a historic 
feature especially in the stations near the river that seemed to 
get stronger at low tide 
we reckoned it would be better to have a nicer aroma like 
in a bathroom he said as a cloying chemical scent drifted up 
the stairway from the track 
like potpourri sachets buried in a lingerie drawer small paper 
packets of fragrance have been hidden behind seats on each car 
when a passenger leans back the packet emits a whiff of apple 
blossoms roses hyacinths lemons mandarins wood or a sea breeze 
