<TEXT>
a house committee that last year focused on 
helping children born addicted to drugs is shifting its attention 
to highrisk mothers 
a former drug addict and alcoholic who blames her substance 
abuse for her daughters retardation told her story thursday as the 
house select committee on children youth and families launched an 
investigation into these womens needs 
the woman identified only as kathleen x said she was 14 when 
she began using heroin and alcohol 
she said that over the next 16 years she had five children two 
are normal two died in infancy and one is mentally retarded 
diagnosed this year as suffering from fetal alcohol syndrome 
we now recognize that fetal alcohol syndrome is one of the 
greatest causes of birth defects and mental retardation in the 
united states said iris smith project director of the georgia 
addiction pregnancy and parenting program in atlanta 
infants born to alcoholic women are often premature have low 
birth weight and later display learning or behavioral disorders 
growth retardation and deficits in memory or attention smith told 
the house panel 
kathleen x testified that she would promise her children she 
would stop using drugs and alcohol but i could never keep that 
promise 
she said she finally became clean six years ago when she entered 
a longterm treatment program she is now regional director of 
community outreach and education for a drug treatment center in the 
maryland suburbs of washington 
committee chairman george miller dcalif noted that kathleen 
x is white and grew up in an affluent area he said her story 
illustrated that the problem affects all socioeconomic groups 
dr sheila b blume of south oaks hospital in amityville ny 
said efforts must be made to identify addicted women early 
pregnancy is the best time to treat an alcoholic woman or a 
chemically dependent woman she said the incentive to have the 
