<TEXT>
fortysix australian veterans some 
over 100 years old left today for turkey to commemorate the world 
war ii campaign at gallipoli regarded as one of the great military 
defeats of the war 
they flew on board a specially configured qantas boeing 747300 
jet that included a minihospital staffed by royal australian air 
force surgeons in case any of the veterans became ill during the 
trip 
prime minister bob hawke and other members of the government sat 
in the back and the veterans traveled firstclass in front of the 
plane 
the oldest was 103 and the trip was expected to be difficult 
for some of the veterans all at least 90 to break up the journey 
the group was to spend 30 hours in singapore before flying to the 
site of the battles 
the veterans were scheduled to arrive in istanbul on sunday 
jack hazlitt 92 was a runner or dispatcher of military 
cables at gallipoli 
we thought it was a glorious chance to see the world for 
nothing he said that attitude didnt last long very few of 
us survived you could say im one of the lucky ones 
australia lost more than 8000 soldiers 
most of the australian soldiers were called diggers and 
93yearold george mitchell said the term developed because all 
we did when not fighting was to dig dig and dig trenches 
the veterans will take part in ceremonies on the gallipoli 
peninsula on wednesday to commemorate the troop landings in 1915 by 
australian new zealand british french and indian troops 
in world war i the ottoman turkish empire was allied with 
germany and austria against britain its dominions france and 
russia 
the gallipoli peninsula lies on the northern side of the 
dardanelles strait in northwestern turkey the object of the 
campaign which military historians call the first combined naval 
and land operation of modern warfare was to open the turkish 
straits to russia capture istanbul then known as constantinople 
and take the ottoman empire out of the war 
gallipoli was a battleground for nine months until the invading 
forces were evacuated in december 1915 and january 1916 
the total casualty list for the invaders was 33532 killed 
78518 wounded and 7689 missing of these 8587 australians were 
killed and 19367 wounded 
the battle gave the turks a modern hero kemal ataturk who made 
his name as a military genius in gallipoli 
australia commemorates the campaign each year with a national 
day of remembrance for those killed in the 191418 war and for 
those who gave their lives in other wars 
in the australian consciousness two things stand out about 
gallipoli said bob carr leader of the labor opposition in the 
state of new south wales first the courage and valor of our 
troops and second that it was a defeat a military disaster 
