<TEXT>
a group hunting nazi war criminals said today 
it will give the united states west germany and australia the 
names of 223 lithuanians and poles believed to have taken part in 
the murder of nearly 200000 jews in world war ii 
efraim zuroff israel director of the los angelesbased simon 
wiesenthal center said the names were among 1284 mentioned in 
documents given last year by leibl kunichowsky an elderly 
holocaust suvivor who now lives in sunrise fla to the archives 
of the yad vashem holocaust memorial 
kunichowsky a civil engineer who lived in kaunas lithuania 
went from refugee camp to refugee camp in 194549 taking testimony 
from survivors each statement was signed and witnessed 
unlike other areas of europe where jews died mainly in nazi gas 
chambers the interviews show that many of the jews in lithuania 
were shot by local partisans zuroff said 
they werent deported to death camps he said they were 
murdered locally and the collaborators played an extremely 
significant role often carrying out the killing themselves 
the lists name nazi collaborators suspected of taking part in 
the murder of nearly 200000 jews he said 
so far zuroff said researchers have carefully examined only 
half of kunichowskys list he said there was a chance of 
prosecuting only about onethird of the suspects because many have 
died others are too old to stand trial and some cannot be traced 
because full names and other details are missing 
what we will be able to achieve in bringing some to trial is 
only symbolic justice which will serve as a warning to the 
murderers of tomorrow he said 
zuroff said the names of 38 prime suspects will be sent to the 
us justice departments office of special investigations next 
week the names of 130 other suspected collaborators will be turned 
over to the west german embassy and 55 will be given to the 
australian embassy on monday 
other lists of names will be sent soon to canada and england 
kunichowsky had kept his material in hopes of writing a book 
but he turned the documents over to yad vashem last year 
the weisenthal center researchers crosschecked the names with 
other records at yad vashem and files from an international red 
cross tracing service in west germany some of those listed were 
already known as war crimes suspects but most were new zuroff 
said 
he said the names would not be made public so as not to tip off 
the suspects and because in some cases further investigation is 
needed to establish identity 
the 1683 pages of testimony were taken in yiddish the 
daytoday language of many european jews and contain graphic 
accounts of the terror faced by 171 jewish communities that were 
uprooted 
 
