although a washington newspaper article published in 1923 
claimed that some years ago it was not unusual for 100 gavels or 
more to be smashed in one congress broken gavels are a rarity 
today 
their replacement is necessary instead because the speakers 
like to autograph their gavels and present them as gifts to 
constituents friends or to fellow legislators who have steered 
major bills to final passage 
veteran house parliamentarians recall that some house speakers 
notably sam rayburn of texas have wielded their gavels with a 
heavy hand but none has banged one into smithereens in recent 
memory 
former speaker thomas p oneill a big irishman from boston 
frequently tapped gently with his gavels handle to persuade 
lawmakers to quiet down 
one of the loudest gavelbangers was former rep richard 
bolling dmo who presided over floor debate and voting on scores 
of bills from the speakers chair during his 34year house career 
bolling interviewed by telephone from his retirement home in 
rural maryland remembered breaking two gavels in those years 
fortunately nobody got hurt he said 
