<TEXT>
a family that has been ranching for four 
decades has learned that becoming more environmentally sensitive 
deosnt mean sacrificing profits 
the sims family headed by 84yearold patriarch roy sims is 
one of a few wyoming ranch owners using an innovative grazing 
technique that increases profits as it improves the land 
were trying to make a living but not at the expense of the 
land said 35yearold scott sims who with his brother olin 
and father don own and operate the 10000acre mcfadden land and 
livestock co 
the family was awarded wyomings 1989 outstanding conservation 
farmer and rancher award and sees this sundays earth day 1990 as 
an opportunity to illustrate that ranchers care about the land 
weve got environmentalists accusing livestock men of tearing 
up the earth olin sims said i hope its a time 
environmentalists realize ranchers are environmentalists too 
a visit to the southern wyoming ranch on a warm april afternoon 
found bawling calves stumbling alongside their mothers on meadows 
that have only recently turned from a frozen gray to spring green 
cottonwoods and elms cast long shadows across a frothing creek 
bulging with snow melt 
but a closer look reveals that the ranch operations are not 
typical 
last year scott and olin sims began using the intensive grazing 
technique instead of allowing their hundreds of cows to roam 
freely over large expanses they sliced the land into small 
pastures so cattle graze each section intensively for two to three 
days before being moved onto another plot 
with 300 cows denuding 300 acres instead of one cow on 40 acres 
munching here and there grass is allowed to regrow and much 
erosion is eliminated 
were severe grazing you go back the next year and its the 
nicest grass on the ranch scott sims explained 
on the heavily grazed sections the cows act as rototillers with 
their trampling and fertilizers with their manure thus encouraging 
healthy new growth rain is absorbed more efficiently on the 
trampled fields rather than running off hard overgrazed land and 
noxious weeds are inhibited and so fewer pesticides are needed 
on the smaller plots bothersome flies that usually hatch in 
manure piles on the open range are trampled to death saving 50 
cents per head in fly abatement costs 
the sims say the healthier lusher grass growth adds an average 
of 20 pounds per weened calf 
if we can double the grass production we can double our 
cattle numbers olin sims said adding that the increased fencing 
pays for itself its nice to see these cows cultivate the land 
and make money for you too 
with this holistic resource management technique we never 
allow that cow to bite that plant a second time before its fully 
recovered he said 
since the cattle are restricted to 5 percent of the ranch at any 
one time the rest of the range is open to wildlife 
the simses also plant 150 trees each year use solar power for 
the electrified fencing and water pumps and maintain enough water 
in the creeks for fish to survive 
with some environmentalists calling for a cattle ban on public 
lands or cattlefree by 93 olin sims said he has to be 
careful a small part of his ranch is leased from the state and 
federal governments 
id like to keep the ranch in the family for years and 
years he said when youve got congress and earth firsters 
breathing down your neck to forbid grazing on public lands youve 
got to be careful its worth it 
asked what his grandfather thought of the changes he and his 
brother have made olin sims said thats the way this whole 
ranch family has been always looking for a better way and not 
getting stuck in a rut 
</TEXT>
