on march 25 1988 police used dogs and a water cannon to 
brutally disperse thousands of believers peacefully rallying in 
downtown bratislava the capital of slovakia for more religious 
freedom 
the crackdown became a symbol of religious persecution in 
slovakia the eastern and strongly catholic part of czechoslovakia 
the same year more than 600000 believers signed a petition for 
greater freedom of worship 
while constraints on religious freedom were tightened followed 
the crushing of the 1968 prague spring reforms the roots of 
churchstate conflict go back to the late 1940s after the 
communists seized power 
authorities suspended diplomatic relations with the vatican on 
april 24 1950 they increased pressure on catholics whose 
allegiance to a foreign power the vatican was seen as a 
threat to stability christianity was erased from official history 
religious education was banned in schools 
the state often refused to give state licences to bishops 
appointed by the vatican leaving up to 10 of czechoslovakias 13 
bishoprics vacant 
in 1970 fearing increasing diplomatic isolation officials 
launched talks on possible renewal of ties it was not until 
czechoslovakias revolution opened the way to spiritual freedom 
that relations with the vatican warmed considerably 
on march 29 1990 an official czechoslovak delegation in rome 
presented pope john paul ii with a request to renew diplomatic 
ties they were formally restored thursday 
czechoslovakia was the third warsaw pact nation to restore 
relations with the holy see after poland and hungary in his drive 
to strengthen the church in the east john paul has visited his 
native poland three times as pope and has scheduled trips to 
hungary and poland next year 
for cardinal frantisek tomasek 90 the visit will be a 
vindication of decades of courageous resistance to communist 
pressures 
it will be a great awakening of consciousness said tomasek 
who spent four years in a labor camp in the 1950s 
some 3 million believers from czechoslovakia as well as 
neighboring poland and hungary are expected to flood prague 
velehrad and the slovak capital of bratislava over the weekend 
when john paul gives his blessing to the countrys estimated 9 
million catholics 
the visit also has an indirect political dimension coming 50 
days before the countrys first free postcommunist elections on 
june 89 
it could significantly boost the popularity of the increasingly 
strong alliance of czechoslovak christian democrats who dominated 
elections in east germany and hungary 
