<TEXT>
east germanys new parliament on friday 
debated the path toward unity with its rich western neighbor in a 
session that highlighted fears about the impact of the planned 
merger 
in an interview to be published saturday east germanys finance 
minister walter romberg warned that 70 percent of the countrys 
factories would need huge support or would not survive economic 
union 
and the chief of the former communist party criticized the 
governments plan for unity and said it would allow west germany to 
colonize east germany 
at the parliamentary session lawmakers united behind prime 
minister lothar de maizieres desire for east germanys currency to 
be valued at the same rate as the mighty west german mark but 
differences quickly emerged over the speed of reunification 
taking advantage of the newly found freedom of protest the 
reformed communist party walked out of the chamber after a member 
of an archconservative party likened the communists to the 
hardliners who ruled east germany 40 years 
the arcconservative joachim hubertus nowack of the german 
social union compared the ousted government to the nazi 
dictatorship that preceded it 
the farmers party one of the many factions in the 400seat 
parliament threatened a blockade of openings in the crumbling 
intergerman border if agricultural markets were threatened by a 
flood of imports during the moves toward a market economy 
gregor gysi who took over the battered communist party and 
oversaw its name change to the party for social democracy urged a 
slow merger and said east germans must have a chance to go 
upright into unification 
he said the constitutions of both germanys should be abolished 
and a new series of laws written for a united nation 
economics minister gerhard pohl rejected this with the comment 
no more socialist experiments 
the coalition government led by de maiziere has proposed that 
east germany adopt the existing west german constitution 
wolfgang thierse of the leftleaning social democrats who 
advocated the slower process before it joined the government 
coalition said the quick route is the realistic way to unity 
but he said the social democrats would fight for revisions 
to the constitution to include the right to housing employment and 
education currently laid down in basic east german law 
the chairman of west germanys social democrats hansjochen 
vogel also cautioned against rapid unification 
it would be terrible if we made mistakes because we proceeded 
too quickly mistakes that the people must put right again vogel 
told reporters he was visiting east berlin for the parliament 
session and a meeting with de maiziere 
in an effort to calm fears about massive unemployment de 
maziere said friday that planned tax incentives and new investment 
laws would help create 500000 new jobs in middlesized enterprises 
this year that would compensate for job losses in large state 
concerns 
in an interview in saturdays edition of the west german neue 
westfaelische newspaper finance minister romberg was quoted as 
saying only 30 percent of east germanys industrial concerns could 
handle competition in a free market economy 
he said that 20 percent would survive only with very heavy 
capital expenditure while 50 percent needed a lot of 
investment the text of the article was released in advance to 
other news media 
