<TEXT>
two republican senators proposed a 
constitutional amendment on friday to overturn a supreme court 
ruling that local government officials could be ordered to increase 
property taxes to finance school desegregation 
the 54 high court ruling on wednesday involved a kansas city 
mo school desegregation case 
sens john danforth and christopher bond both missouri 
republicans introduced the proposed amendment which states 
neither the supreme court nor any inferior court of the united 
states shall have the power to instruct or order a state or 
political subdivision thereof or an official of such state or 
political subdivision to lay or increase taxes 
ratification of a constitutional amendment requires a twothirds 
majority approval by the house and senate and then must be ratified 
by threefourths of the states 
danforth in a statement said he viewed the supreme court 
decision as empowering federal judges to personally impose taxes 
and contended that the constitution gave the power of taxation 
exclusively to the legislative branch 
that decision flatly contradicts a fundamental premise of 
american democracy which predates the constitution itself 
danforth said 
