<TEXT>
the chinese communist party said in a rare public 
release of a major internal document friday that it must resist 
the corrosive influence of the decaying ideologies to maintain 
close ties with the people 
the pledge belied the partys deep anxiety over its ability to 
continue its 41year rule over the worlds most populous nation in 
the wake of plunging public support 
the danger of alienation from the masses may spring up if the 
party does not use its power properly and consciously resist 
the corrosive influence of the decaying ideologies of the 
bourgeoisie and other exploiting classes said the document it 
was approved by a party central committee meeting last month and 
issued via the official xinhua news agency 
the rise or fall of the party and the state depends on whether 
fleshandblood ties with the masses can be maintained and 
developed the central committee document said 
central committee documents are rarely made public and the 
release of this one appeared intended to dramatize the seriousness 
of the partys repeated calls for tightening discipline rooting 
out corruption and improving its public relations 
the communists who took power in 1949 with widespread support 
lost some popularity in the 1950s with forced collectivization and 
in the 1960s with the violent farleftist cultural revolution but 
public disillusionment and cynicism have reached a new high since 
the leadership used the army in june to put down prodemocracy 
protesters killing hundreds and possibly thousands 
the fall of hardline communist governments in east europe and 
ethnic clashes on the edges of this vast nation most recently in 
the moslem west have further undermined the partys stature 
our party and state are presently at a crucial period of 
historical development it said unhealthy tendencies such as 
bureaucracy and individualism and corruptive practices such as 
seeking personal gain through abuse of power have emerged among 
some party cadres in recent years 
we must resolutely rid all malpractices that cut us off from 
the masses and boost our partys cohesive force and fighting 
power it ordered 
among other things the document told party officials to go 
deep down to the grass roots and take part in production so as to 
learn problems firsthand they should shun formalism mix 
with the masses treat them as equals be willing to learn from 
them and avoid putting on airs it said 
party officials must not use public funds to hold banquets and 
must refuse gifts it added in recent years bribes have become an 
implicitly accepted part of doing business in china 
the orders invoked the spirit of the revolutionary era when 
communist soldiers were famous for helping the peasants and not 
taking anything in return since last years protests the partys 
aging leaders have spoken nostalgically of that era and the wartime 
virtues of austere living personal sacrifice and patriotism 
the document said leading officials who hold themselves aloof 
and evoke dissatisfaction from the masses should be fired but 
it did not name anyone one of chinas least popular officials is 
premier li peng who signed the order imposing martial law in 
beijing last year during the protests 
there was speculation he might be removed to placate the public 
but at the recent annual session of chinas legislature he appeared 
firmly in power 
the document reflecting senior leader deng xiaopings policy of 
allowing small democracy said party officials should listen to 
the opinions of ordinary people and not retaliate against criticism 
but it made clear that big democracy pluralism and an end 
to absolute party control is not under consideration 
instead it ordered an increase in marxist education closer 
supervision of the partys 18 million members tightened discipline 
and absolute obedience to central party officials 
