<TEXT>
yugoslavia on friday began requiring 
east europeans to change about 200 in western money to yugolslav 
currency a move that virtually closes its borders to former 
communist neighbors 
thousands of romanians bulgarians soviets and other east 
europeans clogged border crossings early friday hoping to cross 
before the measures took effect according to reports 
yugoslav television showed hundreds of cars some waiting more 
than 12 hours at the vatin border crossing with romania quarrels 
and occasional fistfights broke out between customs officials and 
impatient travelers 
starting friday east european and soviet citizens entering 
yugoslavia through its borders with hungary romania and bulgaria 
had to change the equivalent of 200 in western currencies to 
yugoslav dinars 
many eastern europeans do not generally possess convertible 
western currency 
officially the strict money policy was introduced to prevent 
east europeans from bringing in large quantities of cheap goods 
without paying import duties and selling them at yugoslav flea 
markets 
the borba daily however said the measure was introduced after 
western nations suggested yugoslavia should become a filter 
zone for east europeans seeking asylum in the west 
the shortest road from romania and bulgaria to austria and italy 
is through yugoslavia 
over the past two years thousands of east europeans have poured 
into yugoslavia selling tools canned foods spare parts for 
sovietbuilt cars household utensils and other items at cutrate 
prices 
the influx of east europeans increased markedly this year after 
the dinar became freely convertible this made yugoslavia a 
particularly attractive venue for east europeans who in their own 
countries find it hard to get their hands on large amounts of hard 
currency 
in yugoslavia after selling their wares for dinars they can 
easily exchange the currency for us dollars or west german marks 
</TEXT>
