demobilized at once 
washington backed the contras in their war it then supported 
mrs chamorro in the election and backed her call for the contras 
dissolution 
an additional problem is finding jobs for demobilized fighters 
the contras number about 9000 and the sandinista army is much 
larger although it has suffered from desertion 
mrs chamorros united national opposition alliance is pressing 
the united states for 300 million in aid with a good chunk to be 
devoted to disbanding the contras but even if the aid arrives 
quickly the government wont be able to ease the chronic economic 
problems including unemployment 
the ceasefire took effect thursday and the contras agreed to 
dismantle by june 10 6 weeks after mrs chamorro takes office 
wednesday that represented a concession by the contras who had 
refused to even consider talking about disarming until mrs 
chamorro took power 
the sandinistas had been demanding the contras disband by 
inauguration day but gen ortega said june 10 was soon enough the 
lag will also allow each to assess the others sincerity 
mrs chamorros alliance and the sandinistas signed an agreement 
march 27 that called for shrinking and depoliticizing the army in 
exchange for government recognition of the armys 
professionalism 
mrs chamorros coalition views the contras as both allies and 
problems and some contras suspect the new government would like 
nothing more than for the contras to go away now that electoral 
victory has been achieved 
the coalition gained the most from thursdays agreement even if 
it only postpones the issues of disarming and demobilizing 
the agreements give the new government some not much but some 
political breathing space if it can show that it is in control 
those who are dissatisfied may find themselves isolated and the 
disarmament agreements will have a better chance of sticking and 
bringing peace at last to nicaragua 
</TEXT>
