<TEXT>
here is a chronology of major developments in the prosecution of 
former drexel burnham lambert inc junk bond chief michael milken 
nov 14 1986 stock speculator ivan boesky pays 100 million 
to settle charges of insider trading on information supplied by 
investment banker dennis levine in 1985 and 1986 he also agrees to 
cooperate with investigators and to plead guilty to a single 
criminal charge boesky later is sentenced to three years in prison 
late 1986 published reports link drexel burnham lambert inc 
highyield bond financier michael milken to an illegal insider 
trading network led by boesky 
sept 7 1988 the securities and exchange commission accuses 
drexel milken and three others of violating a wide range of 
securities laws most of them in connection with boesky 
dec 21 drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay 
a record 650 million in fines and restitution to settle the 
biggest securities fraud case in history drexel also must settle 
related sec charges and cooperate with the government investigation 
march 29 1989 a federal grand jury indicts milken his 
brother lowell and former drexel trader bruce lee newberg on 98 
counts of racketeering and fraud largely based on information 
supplied by boesky potential penalties and fines under the counts 
amount to about 12 billion plus possible prison terms 
april 7 the milkens plead innocent newberg enters an innocent 
plea later 
april 13 drexel and the sec announce a settlement of the civil 
fraud case that subjects the firm to federal monitoring for three 
years and forces it to sever ties with milken 
june 15 milken resigns after 19 years at drexel to form his 
own consulting firm lowell milken quits to return to practicing 
law 
sept 11 drexel pleads guilty to six felonies and begins 
paying more than 650 million in fines penalties and interest 
feb 13 1990 drexels parent company files for federal 
bankruptcy court protection after failing to meet shortterm debt 
payments the securities firm once the nations fifthlargest 
starts laying off its 5400 employees 
march 19 prosecutors promise to bring a new indictment with 
broader charges against milken by the week of april 16 
april 4 boesky is released from federal custody after 
completing two years of a threeyear term 
april 19 four months of negotiations intensify between the 
government and milken for a possible plea bargain to settle the 
case as a deadline looms for the new indictment 
april 20 sources say milken agrees to plead guilty to six 
felony counts and pay fines and restitution totaling 600 million 
under a plea agreement with prosecutors 
</TEXT>
