<TEXT>
veterans of world war i who fought in 
the gallipoli campaign left friday for turkey to commemorate one of 
the worst allied defeats in the war to end all wars 
the 46 australians aged 90 to 103 took off on a specially 
outfitted qantas airways boeing 747300 the plane was equipped 
with a minihospital including royal australian air force doctors 
to care for the veterans in case of medical emergency 
the journey for the ceremonies on wednesday will include a 
30hour stop in singapore to give the veterans a rest break the 
trip scheduled for arrival sunday in istanbul is expected to be 
difficult for some 
unlike their crowded wartime trip in a troop ship the veterans 
traveled first class in front of the plane while prime minister bob 
hawke and other government representatives sat in the rear of the 
jet 
some reflected on their first voyage 
we thought it was a glorious chance to see the world for 
nothing said 92yearold jack hazlitt who was a runner or 
military cables dispatcher that attitude didnt last long very 
few of us survived you could say im one of the lucky ones 
gallipoli is the turkish peninsula on the northern side of the 
dardanelles strait allied forces consisting of the britain 
australia new zealand french and indian troops invaded in 1915 in 
an attempt to open the straits to russia capture istanbul then 
known as constantinople and sever the ottoman turkish empire from 
its ally germany 
allied forces fought unsuccessfully for nine months and were 
forced to evacuate in december 1915 and january 1916 
allied casualties were 33532 killed 78518 wounded and 7689 
missing including 8587 australians killed and 19367 wounded 
most of the australian soldiers were called diggers and 
93yearold george mitchell said the term developed because all 
we did when not fighting was to dig dig and dig trenches 
the battle gave the turks a modern hero kemal ataturk who made 
his name as a military genius in gallipoli 
australia commemorates the campaign each year with a national 
day of remembrance for those killed in the wwi and for those who 
died in other wars 
in the australian consciousness two things stand out about 
gallipoli said bob carr leader of the labor opposition in the 
state of new south wales first the courage and valor of our 
troops and second that it was a defeat a military disaster 
</TEXT>
