<TEXT>
secretarygeneral javier perez de cuellar 
will visit the isolated stalinist country of albania in midmay 
un officials confirmed friday 
it will be the first trip by a un secretarygeneral to 
albania the last bastion of hardline communism in eastern europe 
in recent weeks albania has made several recent moves to 
increase ties with the west including the reestablishment of 
telephone communications with the united states and several other 
western nations 
albanian foreign minister reis malile invited perez de cuellar 
to travel to his country when he visited the un general assembly 
in october 
the visit had been announced officially last month and there 
were no further details available friday except that the officials 
said the un chief is expected to spend two days in albania 
un officials said perez de cuellar was also planning trips in 
may to czechoslovakia and hungary two east bloc countries that 
have moved to end four decades of communist rule 
a visit to albania a nation accused of serious human rights 
abuses would make perez de cuellar one of the most senior 
international officials to visit the rigid communist state in 
recent years 
albania lying between greece and yugoslavia on the adriatic 
sea is one of the most isolated countries in the world albanian 
authorities strictly limit foreign visitors and tightly control 
access to foreign broadcasts and books 
despite the restrictions there have been indications of moves 
toward opening to the outside world since the death in 1985 of 
albanian hardline leader enver hoxha hoxha broke relations with 
the soviet union in 1961 because of nikita krushchevs dismantling 
of stalinism 
