<TEXT>
the united states and 31 other member 
nations of the organization of american states on friday formally 
signed a wideranging plan to speed up the hemispheres war against 
drugs 
the 20point declaration of ixtapa unanimously approved friday 
by the countries top law enforcement officers made no mention 
however of extradition 
extradition of suspects especially to the united states has 
been a touchy issue in latin america in recent years made even 
touchier this month by the alleged abduction of a mexican doctor to 
stand trial in los angeles in the 1985 murder of a us drug agent 
the declaration of ixtapa calls for better education and 
prevention starting in grammar schools greater coordination in 
police actions improvements in information exchange and tougher 
laws against the drug trade 
it calls for stronger measures against moneylaundering and 
illegal sales of weapons and explosives and of lab equipment and 
chemicals used in making drugs 
the plan includes a project for economic aid through the inter 
american development bank and like financial institutions to help 
farmers substitute legal crops for highpaying illicit crops such 
as coca leaf poppies and marijuana 
the declaration called for greater cooperation by governments 
for adequate control of their borders with absolute respect 
for the sovereignty and territorial integrity of states 
according to some news reports bounty hunters snatched dr 
humberto alvarez machain 42 from his gynecologists office in 
guadalajara for a large reward put up by the us drug enforcement 
administration 
alvarez is one of 19 mexicans indicted by a us grand jury in 
the tortureslaying of dea agent enrique camarena 
mexico demanded an explanation and attorney general dick 
thornburgh asked dea director william c bennett for a full and 
immediate investigation 
similarly president virgilio barco of colombia has been 
criticized and threatened for extraditing colombian drug suspects 
to the united states 
experts from the oas nations unanimously concluded in a report 
to the assembled justice ministers at the fourday meeting that 
nowhere is the drug problem more serious and pressing than in the 
americas 
latin america is a leading grower and producer of the three 
principal drugs cocaine heroin and marijuana and the united 
states is the worlds leading consumer and center for 
moneylaundering 
enormous profits derived from the drug trade are making it 
possible for transnational criminal organizations to penetrate 
government structures the experts said 
these criminal elements are penetrating legitimate business 
activities and society at all levels corrupting and contaminating 
them and undermining the foundations of states the report 
added 
