israels supreme court on friday blocked the 
eviction of jewish settlers living in a compound in the christian 
quarter of jerusalems old city temporarily setting aside an order 
by the attorney general 
the 150 settlers can remain in the four 100yearold buildings 
near the church of the holy sepulcher until the high court hears 
more arguments next week on an appeal for the settlers to remain 
attorney general yosef harish on thursday ordered their 
immediate eviction from the 72room complex owned by the greek 
orthodox church harish said he wanted to prevent further 
deterioration of jewishchristian relations 
the church claims a former tenant illegally sold his user rights 
to the building to the settlers 
the april 11 move by the settlers into the christian quarter 
sparked angry protests by arab christians and moslems they fear 
the group is leading a campaign to eventually push all palestinians 
out of the walled old city 
after the high court allowed the settlers to stay a half dozen 
