<TEXT>
the number of illegal aliens caught 
entering the country per year dropped nearly by half from 1986 to 
1988 but sanctions on employers played a small role in cutting the 
flow said a study released thursday 
employer sanctions in the immigration reform and control act 
alone slowed the rate of illegal entry into the united states by 
less than 20 percent according to a joint study by the rand corp 
and the washingtonbased urban institute 
the study concluded that if the sanctions portion of the law was 
expected to merely stop the increase of illegal immigrants the 
reform act has succeeded 
but if officials expected a major drop in such numbers then the 
sanctions have failed and they probably should be reviewed by 
congress the studys authors said 
among the considerations would be increasing the level of 
enforcement or considering the cost of continuing the sanctions 
against such limited results 
congress approved the immigration act in november 1986 the 
employersanctions section was one of the most controversial 
for more than a year the immigration and naturalization service 
conducted seminars and contacted businesses about their obligations 
under the law then businesses were checked for compliance 
only in 1989 were repeat offenders prosecuted and punished for 
disobeying the law 
the study looked at various statistics to make its conclusions 
including counts of people passing through canyon zapata north of 
tijuana mexico a favored spot of illegal entry of the united 
states 
the raw data showed more than 17 million apprehensions in 1986 
down to just over 1 million apprehensions in 1988 the last year 
for which the statistics were available 
immigration waiting lists of several countries also were 
investigated researchers theorized that if immigration reforms 
were effective more people would be convinced to try entering the 
united states legally 
also reviewed were the wages for jobs traditionally taken by 
illegal immigrants dishwashing and car washing a rise in wages 
would indicate a decrease in the supply of such workers but no 
rise was detected 
alone none of our data sets provides conclusive evidence that 
employer sanctions have or have not reduced undocumented 
immigration the study said together the preponderance of the 
evidence points to some decline in the flow 
</TEXT>
