<TEXT>
a new securities rule designed to help big 
institutions investing more than 100 million also should benefit 
people across the country who never dabble on wall street 
regulators said 
the securities and exchange commissions rule 144a will make it 
easier for big banks insurance companies and pension funds to 
trade in unregistered stocks and bonds that may not be sold to the 
general public 
the sec requires companies offering stock to the public to 
register and make extensive disclosures about their ownership 
financing and other issues to protect american investors 
but the agency voted thursday to ease restrictions on trading 
privately offered securities which arent required to register and 
arent bound by disclosure regulations 
the 40 vote applies only to institutional investors that can 
prove they are big enough to handle the risk of dealing in 
unregistered securities but sec chairman richard c breeden said 
the measure would have a broader impact 
we hope this rule will have a beneficial effect even on people 
who dont buy securities at all breeden told reporters after the 
meeting 
to the extent that we can reduce the cost of us companies 
raising capital thatll benefit the people who work for those 
companies benefit the us economy broadly by helping make us more 
competitive 
breeden noted that some estimates put the market for privately 
placed securities at 1704 billion last year up from 158 
billion in 1980 
but two congressional leaders expressed concern about the 
possible development of a twotiered securities market for us 
investors one public and one private 
in a letter to breeden released after thursdays vote reps 
john d dingell dmich and edward j markey dmass asked the 
sec to report periodically to congress on the new rules impact 
dingell powerful head of the house energy and commerce 
committee and markey chairman of its finance committee which 
oversees the sec said they also were concerned that rule 144a may 
be beyond the scope of the powers of the commission because it 
allows for exemption from registration and thus disclosure 
requirements 
full and fair disclosure of the character of securities sold 
across state lines is a key element of federal securities law they 
said 
the rule sets a 100 million threshold for participating in the 
private placement market to screen out unsophisticated investors 
who might not be able to make wise choices without the disclosures 
required on public offerings 
registered brokerdealers that either own and manage 10 million 
in securities or act as riskless principals for qualified 
institutional buyers are exempt from the 100 million requirement 
banks and savings and loans on the other hand must have a net 
worth of 25 million in addition to holding at least 100 million 
in securities 
the move is expected to lower the cost of raising money for us 
companies while wooing foreign corporations sometimes put off by 
onerous us disclosure requirements to raise capital here 
the sec also approved rule changes that would make the national 
association of securities dealers portal trading system the market 
place for such unregistered securities and clarify regulations 
governing foreign transactions of unregistered securities 
this is an historic day for the commission and its 
international program said breeden who has been pushing to make 
the us securities laws and markets more competitive with foreign 
markets 
