<TEXT>
it probably was inevitable that after the 
debtengorged 1980s one of the first scares of the 90s would be 
the fear that a shortage of credit would tilt the economy into 
recession 
after all with estimates of the thrift bailout now reaching as 
high as 500 billion and regulators keeping a closer eye on the 
books savings and loans wont be pushing out loans like the good 
old days 
banks also are feeling the pinch of bad loans as last weeks 
first quarter results showed clearly citicorp the nations 
biggest bank and biggest real estate lender reported a 56 percent 
drop in profits largely because of problems with loans for real 
estate and corporate takeovers 
the situation has raised anxiety on capitol hill responding to 
a question from a congressman worried about businesses at home 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan said last week that a 
large majority of the nations top banks had become less 
willing to make construction or land development loans 
does that add up to a growthsnuffing credit crunch many 
analysts say not quite to the extent that some borrowers are 
getting turned down it may not be a bad thing 
brian j fabbri chief economist at midland montagu economics in 
new york says evidence seems clear that banks are extending less 
credit the amount of big certificates of deposit or interbank 
deposits banks buy the raw material for their lending actually 
has contracted over the past year he says 
one reason for the pullback is the growing effect of an 
international agreement on capital standards which will require 
banks to hold capital equal to 8 percent of their assets as a 
cushion against losses fabbri says the standards require more 
capital for riskier assets so banks are likely to cut back first 
on loans for smaller companies construction and takeovers he says 
i think were clearly at a point where were witnessing banks 
and thrifts reducing their extensions fabbri says the small 
the less creditworthy borrowers no doubt will have less wherewithal 
to expand 
but some other economists think the problem isnt a lack of 
money to lend its a shortage of borrowers 
big companies havent been borrowing much from banks in recent 
months because it has been far cheaper to raise money via 
commercial paper the market for corporate ious says kevin logan 
chief economist at swiss bank corp in new york thirtyday 
commercial paper costs just over 83 percent today compared with 
the bank prime rate of 10 percent 
