<TEXT>
a major creditrating agencys decision to 
review the health of citicorps debts reflects the hard times the 
banking industry is enduring with weakening foreign and real estate 
loans 
several other insitutions already have had ratings on their 
securities downgraded as credit agencies express concern over the 
quality of the debt 
its hardly unusual said mara hildeman a senior analyst at 
moodys investor services inc which put some 31 billion of 
citicorps senior debt undeis month downgraded 28 billion of first 
chicago corp senior debt by one notch to a3 from a2 and last 
month marine midland banks inc saw moodys lower its rating on 
13 billion of its senior debt to baa1 from a3 
moodys review of citicorp the nations largest banking company 
with 230 billion in assets didnt send tremors through the 
banking community 
the industry is already shaken said mark gross a senior 
vice president at ibca inc the new york arm of the londonbased 
rating agency the review of citicorp just adds to it 
a lower credit rating could make it more expensive for citicorp 
to borrow money by prompting investors to demand higher interest to 
compensate for increased risk the ratings have no affect on 
customer deposits 
currently citicorp outranks many banking institutions its 
senior debt carries an a1 rating well above moodys current 
rating of some of chemical banks debt 
moodys characterizes a1 bonds as possessing many favorable 
investment attributes but elements may be present which 
suggest a susceptibility to impairment sometime in the future 
moodys pointed specifically to citicorps nonperforming loans 
in real estate and to developing countries as well as loans made in 
highly leveraged transactions like buyouts financed mainly with 
debt 
according to ibca 7 percent of citicorps real estate loans 
excluding residential mortgages were nonperforming in 1989 
though that figure does not rank citicorp at much greater risk than 
its peers analysts expect the amount of nonperforming real estate 
loans those on which payments are not being made to increase 
citicorp is fairly geographically diverse in its real estate 
portfolio but nevertheless given their location in new york they 
have a fairly large concentration of loans in the northeast 
where the economy is expected to deteriorate hildeman said 
about 5 percent of citicorps highly leveraged transactions were 
nonperforming the fifthworst showing in ibcas review of 50 major 
banks but citicorp has 78 billion in highly leveraged loans 
outstanding roughly twice as much as the next biggest player 
in comparison ibca said that in 1989 chase manhattan bank had 
45 billion in outstanding highly leveraged debt 11 percent of 
which was nonperforming 
in terms of capital ratios in which assets are adjusted to 
reflect total risk to the corporation citicorp barely met the 
governments minimum 4 percent requirement with a ratio of 404 
percent citicorp ranked 49th out of 51 institutions although the 
bank is in the process of raising its capital ratios 
once a company is under review moodys likes to act quickly 
before speculation runs rampant 
i dont see how they can downgrade citicorp very much 
said anthony naylor a senior vice president of fixedincome 
securities at rodman amp renshaw inc and one notch isnt going to 
make a whole lot of difference citicorp isnt in the credit 
squeeze that some regional banks are its so diversified he 
said 
if moodys takes action it might encourage citicorp 
management to be more quick in terms of what they do to remedy the 
situation said richard mueller an analyst at duff amp phelps in 
chicago 
no bank likes to see any downgrading but it brings more 
sharply into focus the issues management has to deal with he 
said 
earlier this week citicorp reported its firstquarter earnings 
declined 56 percent mainly because of problems with weakening real 
estate loans 
