<DOCNO> AP900420-0260 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
recommendations designed to establish 
worldwide controls against laundering of hundreds of billions of 
dollars by drug dealers were announced thursday by an international 
task force 
the 40 action recommendations should establish a network 
of comprehensive programs to address money laundering and will 
facilitate greater cooperation in international investigations 
prosecutions and property seizures deputy treasury secretary 
john e robson told reporters 
the recommendations were adopted by the financial action task 
force on money laundering last feb 7 in paris and announced 
simultaneously thursday by the participating nations robson headed 
the us delegation on the panel 
the task force was established following last summers economic 
summit of the group of seven nations in paris to assess current 
antimoney laundering efforts and to consider additional 
preventive efforts in this field 
in addition to the g7 nations of britain canada france 
germany italy japan and the united states other task force 
members included austria australia belgium luxembourg the 
netherlands spain sweden and switzerland and the european 
community 
robson said the recommendations will be on the agenda at the 
july meeting of the g7 nations that president bush will host 
houston 
the task force report noted that the united nations estimated 
drug trafficking proceeds worldwide at 300 billion in 1987 money 
traffickers use a complex web of financial transactions to hide the 
money in their accounts 
the financial action task force was born of the ideas that 
narcotics trafficking and money laundering are inextricably 
connected and that money laundering is an international problem 
that requires an international solution robson said 
countries must link together to have strong domestic 
antimoney laundering programs for detection and prosecution and 
must cooperate freely with each other in the many cases that cross 
international borders he said 
central to the recommendations is that financial institutions 
must be the first line of defense by reporting suspicious dealings 
by their customers robson said 
specifically the task force recommends that as in the united 
states financial institutions must be able to report suspicious 
transactions to law enforcement in good faith free from fear of 
liability under secrecy laws he said 
suspicious transaction reporting has proven to be vary 
valuable to us law enforcement he added 
robson said other recommendations include requirements that 
financial institutions have procedures to identify their customers 
and maintain adequate records about customers and their 
transactions 
in most cases current us laws and regulations are in 
conformance with the recommendations robson said 
robson said the announcement of the recommendations was the 
starting point of missionary efforts to attract support 
throughout the international community 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

