<TEXT>
massachusetts lawmakers in a show of unity 
urged the bush administration thursday to block a hostile takeover 
of norton co of worcester mass a maker of industrial abrasives 
arguing that norton is the leader in a field with defense and 
national security applications all 13 members of the states 
congressional delegation attended a news conference at the capitol 
calling for federal action against the proposed takeover by great 
britains btr plc 
norton is worcester said us rep joseph early dmass 
norton is the worlds leading manufacturer of abrasives and the 
largest employer in worcester 
the 3100 norton employees would see their jobs jeopardized 
early said if a foreign owner decided to relocate or sell off 
nortons assets such as plant equipment and patents 
the delegation members signed a joint letter to president bush 
urging him to step in and block the takeover early said the 
delegation would unveil legislation next week designed to make it 
easier for the president to stop bid 
a law already on the books allows the president following an 
investigation to block a foreign takeover if it would threaten 
national security but it has only been invoked once 
a btr spokesman who asked to remain anonymous said the 
existing law is inapplicable to btr 
btr and its subsidiaries in the us have sensitive and 
secretive clearance with the department of defense and other 
federal government agencies the spokesman said we believe 
those clearances are more sensitive than nortons 
the btr spokesman added that btr has no plans to move the norton 
headquarters or lay off workers 
the stance taken by the congressional delegation came a day 
after gov michael s dukakis signed a law that would prevent btr 
from wresting immediate control over the norton board 
the law requires massachusetts companies to elect directors over 
staggered terms with onethird being elected at a time that would 
prevent btr from replacing a majority of directors at the norton 
annual meeting scheduled for next thursday 
norton tried to delay the meeting for two months but that move 
was blocked this week by the us court of appeals 
norton also has filed a lawsuit in federal court alleging that 
state law prohibits btr from exercising any voting power at 
nortons shareholders meeting btr called nortons claim 
frivolous 
a key player in the effort to involve president bush in the 
