the upjohn co has agreed to pay 18 
million to settle a federal lawsuit stemming from more than 1000 
waste water discharge permit violations at the companys north 
haven fine chemicals plant two environmental groups announced 
thursday 
upjohn will contribute just over 12 million to the new haven 
foundation to establish a trust fund for projects beneficial to the 
quinnipiac river new haven harbor and their watersheds the groups 
said 
the remainder of the settlement will be used to cover the legal 
costs incurred by the connecticut fund for the environment and the 
natural resources defense council said kate robinson senior staff 
attorney for cfe 
robinson said she believed it was the largest pollution penalty 
ever paid for permit violations in connecticut 
the two environmental groups sued upjohn in 1985 under a 
citizens suit provision of the federal clean water act for 
exceeding limits on the toxic materials it could discharge into the 
quinnipiac river 
a federal judge in hartford ruled in 1987 that upjohn was liable 
for more than 1000 permit violations and a hearing to determine 
the fine was held in late december and early january a settlement 
was reached then but details had to be worked out robinson said 
by settling the case the environmental groups were able to make 
sure the money paid by upjohn is used to help clean up the 
quinnipiac robinson said 
had the court imposed a penalty the money would have gone to 
the federal treasury she said 
upjohn had argued that it had done all that was possible to 
treat its industrial waste and that it viewed permit standards 
established in 1983 as goals and not enforceable limits 
we regret the misunderstanding which followed our installation 
of what was at the time the best available technology to control 
our waste water discharges pete mass a spokesman at upjohns 
kalamazoo mich headquarters said thursday 
on the settlement he said we are pleased that this is not 
only finished but that most of the proceeds will be used for such a 
worthy cause as improving the quinnipiac river 
upjohn announced in december its plan to phase out operations at 
the north haven plant over three years 
