<TEXT>
president carlos salinas de gortari who has 
made economic liberalization one of the hallmarks of his 
administration has opened up the newsprint monopoly to competition 
productora e importadora de papel sa known as pipsa has had 
the monopoly on newsprint production and importation since its 
founding in 1935 
by controlling the supply of newsprint and extending credit on 
pipsa bills the government has been able to muzzle its enemies by 
controlling the supply of newsprint and credit the government has 
at times withheld newsprint supplies from critics 
but that control ends friday when anybody can produce or import 
newsprint 
salinas announced the change thursday in remarks at a special 
meeting of pipsas board of directors made up of newspaper 
publishers at the presidential palace 
the president said competition would make pipsa more efficient 
and fortify press freedom 
a stronger pipsa will strengthen our democracy salinas said 
although they now have the freedom to purchase newsprint from 
other suppliers publishers said they were unsure whether they 
would switch right away 
when salinas proposed last year that pipsa be liquidaded 
publishers howled in protest pipsa for many years allowed 
cashshort buyers to pay when they were able and the company was a 
perennial moneyloser 
but last year pipsa turned around and made nearly 12 million 
in profits 
mexico which manufactured 400000 tons of newsprint last year 
is the worlds 11thlargest producer but domestic production cant 
keep up with demand last year mexican publishers bought 430000 
tons of newsprint 
interior minister fernando gutierrez barrios said that after 
turning a profit pipsa is an efficient and productive public 
company which guarantees the existence of a free and pluralistic 
press that mexican society requires 
the head of pipsa said salinas announcement opens the options 
for newspapers 
rene villareal the organizations director general said he 
didnt know whether newsprint prices would rise or fall 
like anything the market will determine the prices he said 
publishers enthusiastically supported the move 
its an excellent decision it opens the possibilities to buy 
on the free market it will be very beneficial for all 
publishers said benjamin wong castaneda publisher of punto 
but wong like other publishers said it was too soon to say 
whether he would seek a new supplier 
